          <p class='first-para'>
            Obviously I welcome that proposal. The noble Lord said that guidance was not necessary or desirable. I would respond to that by saying, "By definition it is; otherwise I would not have
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_74gc' title='Col. 74GC &mdash; HL Deb 24 June 2003 vol 650 c74GC' name='column_74gc' href='#column_74gc' rel='bookmark'>74GC</a>
            been asked to propose the amendment". I would also hope that officials will talk to the Electoral Commission to see what it has in mind as regards local polls and whether it feels that any issues surrounding local polls need to be specifically addressed. The issue of accessible buildings, for example, has been touched on. In my own experience, prefabricated buildings&#x2014;caravans&#x2014;are often difficult to access, more so than a conventional building.</p><p>
            I go back to where I started, which was whether or not accessibility should be a condition of having a local poll or whether, as was proposed, the condition should have regard to guidance. I also had in mind that it would be awkward if the poll were invalidated because regard had not been had to the guidance, which could leave people in an awful tangle. The noble Baroness, Lady Gould, probably has far more practical experience about these issues than the rest of the Committee put together. I am particularly grateful for her support. I beg leave to withdraw the amendment.
