            The amendment is eminently reasonable because it gives the parents of young children the right not to work. It does not state that they do not have to work at all. As the noble Lord, Lord Northbourne, said, in recent times there has been a great deal of activity in government departments to promote family-friendly policies. However, Ministers have also stated recently that it is a good thing for mothers to go out to work and that their children do not suffer as a result. That is a debatable point. However, if parents make a genuine choice to go out to work&#x2014;or go out to work because of necessity, which sadly is so often the case&#x2014;it is not a very tall order to ask that provision be made to give them a right in law not to be required to work, in the way set out in the amendment.</p><p>
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_77gc' title='Col. 77GC &mdash; HL Deb 24 June 2003 vol 650 c77GC' name='column_77gc' href='#column_77gc' rel='bookmark'>77GC</a>
